The paper focuses on developing a new system for second-factor authentication that provides strong protection against token faults and backdoors. This falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) and cybersecurity (cs.CY). The paper also discusses implementing new privacy defenses to prevent cross-origin token-fingerprinting attacks, which could fall under the categories of software engineering (cs.SE) and social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper presents new lightweight two-party protocols for generating cryptographic keys and ECDSA signatures, which could fall under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it involves developing new algorithms.
